The paper deals with lower bounds for parameterized problems, which are typically studied in the computational complexity (cs.CC) and data structures (cs.DS) sub-categories. The use of ${\rm AC}^0$ circuits suggests a connection to circuit complexity and Boolean functions, which are also studied in cs.CC. The planted clique conjecture, which is used to prove one of the lower bounds, is a well-known problem in graph theory and combinatorics (cs.DM). The paper also mentions connections to descriptive complexity (cs.LO) and proof theory, which are related to the study of logic and formal languages. Finally, the parameterized halting problem mentioned in the abstract suggests a connection to computability theory (cs.CGT).
